      <P align=justify><I></I>&nbsp;</P>
      <P align=center><FONT face=Arial size=4><I>Long QT syndrome (LQTS) is a 
      heart disease manifesting itself by a prolonged QT interval on the ECG and 
      clinically by a propensity for tachyarrhythmias, causing syncopes and 
      sudden cardiac death. LQTS may be drug-induced, but recently mutations in 
      genes coding for cardiac ion-channels have been shown to cause the 
      hereditary forms, <A 
      href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/htbin-post/Omim/dispmim?192500">Romano-Ward 
      syndrome (RWS)</A> and <A 
      href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/htbin-post/Omim/dispmim?220400">Jervell 
      and Lange-Nielsen Syndrome (JLNS)</A>. This site aims at providing updated 
      information on the molecular genetics of Long QT syndrome for scientists 
      and health providers. The site is located at <A 
      href="http://www.ssi.dk/en/">Statens Serum Institut</A>, Copenhagen, and 
      maintained by the <A 
      href="http://www.ssi.dk/graphics/html/lqtsdb/mcgroup.htm">Molecular 
      Cardiology Group</A>, headed by <A 
      href="http://www.ssi.dk/graphics/html/lqtsdb/mic.htm">Michael 
      Christiansen</A>.The searchable mutation database is curated by <A 
      href="http://www.ssi.dk/graphics/html/lqtsdb/mic.htm">Michael 
      Christiansen</A> (to whom diagnostic and analytical questions should be 
      directed), <A href="http://www.ssi.dk/graphics/html/lqtsdb/lal.htm">Lars 
      Allan Larsen</A>, and <A 
      href="http://www.ssi.dk/graphics/html/lqtsdb/psa.htm">Paal Skytt 
      Andersen</A>. </I></FONT></P>
